{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_bullock_ver01/data/sn82016181/00516999615/1937112701/0901.xml":{"full_text":"Berlin's Bid for Trade Pact With U. S. Gets Cool Reception\nBy RAYMOND CLAPPER\nGermany has been checking around in Washington trying\nto find some way of getting in under the Hull reciprocal trade\nprogram.\nBut the reception was cool and there was no sale.\nGermany has been advised that it is hopeless to consider\nnegotiations without first making major alterations in fascist\ntrade practices.\nMany\u2014probably most\u2014of our officials are not in sympathy,\nas individuals, with the Hitler regime,\nag 4 While they would not allow the official\nateesn record to say so, some of them feel so\nwain strongly about this that they would rather\nOF h not see a reciprocal trade agreement ne\ng aas gotiated with Germany at this time.\n99 8\nUnquestionably a\nGerman American\n8\ns\nClapper\ntrade agreement now would be used for\npolitical purposes both abroad and at\nhome, and altho little is said about these\nbroader considerations they undoubtedly\nI have a strong influence here. The Hitler\nI regime is extremely unpopular in Con\ngress and a trade agreement with Ger\nmany would be used as a vehicle for at\ntack on the whole reciprocal program.\nAbroad, such an agreement might be used to weaken the align\nment of democratic powers which are struggling to restrain\nthe German-Italian-Japanese bloc of aggressor nations.\nIt Seems to Me\nBy Heywood\nBROUN\nIN THE controversy between the\nPresident and the Professor it\nseems to me that the lady is right\nonly in theory, while the substance\nof the argument lies with Mr. Roose\nvelt.\nThe lady who trumped up the\nBroun\ncharges is Prof.\nJanet R. Aiken,\nof Columbia Uni\nversity. And in\nher indictment\nshe asserts that,\nspeaking from\nthe back of a\ntrain at Chey\ne n n e.\nWy o.,\nFranklin Delano\nRoosevelt did\nsay,\n\u201cEngineers\nare human just\nlike I am.\u201d\nAccor ding to\npress reports from the Nation's Capi\ntal, the Chief Executive sought\n\u201csmilingly\u201d to pin the blame upon\nthe reporters who covered the good\nwill tour. But in this case he was\ntripped by the official transcript.\nAccording to\nthe stenographic\nrecord, he was not misquoted.\nIt seems to me that the President\nchose law grounds for his defense.\nHe should have entered a demurrer\nin the first place. If my legal ad\nvice is competent I understand that\nwhen one demurs he admits the\nfacts but adds as questioning, \u201cSo\nwhat?\u201d\nCertainly it is easy to\nthink of crimes which transcend\nthat of using \u201clike\u201d as a conjunction\nin Wyoming.\nBut if the court of public opinion\nsupported Prof. Aiken, then the\nPresident should have come forward\nwith a plea for freedom in rear plat\nform speeches. He should have\nasked for license and not liberty.\nL\nANGUAGE dwindles and dies un\nless a comfortable gulf is to be\nset between written and spoken Eng\nlish. This is not artificial distinc\ntion but an instinct in all living\nkind. Try it on your dog. Under\noath I am willing to testify that it\nis all but impossible to teach a dog\nto \u201clie down.\" The approach is far\neasier if at the very beginning you\nuse the common \u201cLay down.\" The\ndog will respect the master who uses\nthe incorrect form and continue to\ndespise and disobey the precisionist.\nI don\u2019t know why, but it seems to\nbe true that no pedant is a hero to\nhis pet.\nTHERE used to be a wholly un\nfounded anecdote in Cam\nbridge concerning A. Lawrence Lowell\nand a freshman beer night. Ac\ncording to the legend, the president\nof the university was walking thru a\ncollege dormitory late one night\nwhen he heard a terrific racket in\none of the rooms.\nRapping on the door, he cried\nout, \u201cDesist immediately,\" and an\nundergraduate voice responded,\n\u201cSays who?\u201d\n\u201cIt\u2019s me\u2014President Lowell,\u201d an\nswered the distinguished historian.\n\u201cGet away, from that door, you\ndope, or Ill knock you for a row of\nashcans,\u201d came back a voice not yet\nquite set in the Harvard accent.\n\u201cYou old fool, if you really were\nPresident Lowell you would have\nsaid, \u201cIt is I,\u201d and, according to the\nanecdote, A. Lawrence Lowell went\naway abashed and knocked on no\nmore doors that night.\nBut, of course, President Roosevelt\ncould have used the simplest answer\nof all. He might have told Prof.\nAiken the truth\u2014which is simply\nthis:\u2014\u201cBad grammar never cost\nanybody any votes in Wyoming.\u201d\nThe question came up soon after the return of German Am\nbassador Dieckoff from Berlin several weeks ago. Germany\nsent a communication to the State Department, which was\nfollowed up by personal conversations.\nThe editor of The\nFrankfurter Zeitung also has been here recently sounding out\nSecretary Hull, Secretary Wallace, Assistant Secretary of State\nSayre and Treasury officials. At no time was any encourage\nment given to these German overtures.\nWithout having to stand on the political objections to the\nproposal, officials offered other objections equally compelling.\nMost important is the difficulty concerning the unconditional\nmost-favored-nation clause.\nHull insists upon this in every\ntrade agreement. It is the corner stone of his program. This\nprovision requires that each party grant to the other the bene\nfit of the most favorable import conditions which it gives to\nany nation.\nGermany\u2019s foreign trade is built largely upon\nbarter deals protected by special import privileges.\nFor in\nstance. it will grant Brazil special privileges in a barter deal\nfor cotton.\nDenmark will receive a special arrangement for\nexporting eggs or butter to Germany.\nUnder any reciprocal\ntreaty the United States would insist upon receiving the same\nadvantages as either of those countries, for example.\nObviously it is impossible now for Germany to meet that\ncondition. It would require complete and basic alteration of\nher foreign trade program. That gets to the central pur\npose of the Hull program. Its purpose is to break down these\nSIDE GLANCES\nby George Clark\nr\nT\nT\nWE\nT\nT\nI\nW* V\nM-2r\n\u201cWill you look in the want ads and see if anyone wants a\ngood cook?\u201d\nA BLURB TO THE MASTER\nQNCE there was a press agent whose blurbs were welcomed\nin every newspaper of the land. And now Dexter Fellows\nis dead.\nDexter Fellows was head ballyhoo man for Ringling Bros,\nand Barnum Bailey, the Greatest Show on Earth. He was,\ntho not a circus owner, the true descendant of old Phineas T.\nBarnum, and as the years rolled on and he no longer appeared\nin person in the hinterland, he became practically a legend.\nFellows\u2019 annual interviews in New York and the appear\nance in print of his tall tales of what the new and improved\ncircus, Bigger and Better Than Ever, was to offer, was the\nbreath of spring broadcast over a nation, weary of winter\u2019s\nsnow.\n\u201cHe has an adjective factory in Connecticut,\u201d reporters have\nsaid. \u201cHe has traveled across Australia in the pouch of a kan\ngaroo. Gorilla mothers in the wilds of central Africa hush\ntheir babies with the sound of his name. He has (God bless\nhim) rowed along the edge of the Gulf Stream to determine\nthe exact date of the beginning of spring.\u201d\nIn a world grown old in troubles, the passing of a man with\nDexter Fellows\u2019 serious regard for the innocent art of make\nbelieve is not to be lightly mourned.\nI\n\u25a01\nComment of Riders on Street Cars\nEditor, The News:\nHOW about schooling street car\nmotormen to drive these con\ntraptions without knocking you\ndown or throwing you out of your\nseat every time they stop and start?\nHow about stopping on corners in\nstead of in the middle of the blocks?\nHow about instructing these operat\ners to wait for riders at transfer\npoints when two cars arrive at the\nsame time? How about the police\nticketing motormen for running\nthru red lights?? How about a rid\ners\u2019 strike? Let\u2019s hike it and like\nit, while we\u2019re still altogether.\nBLACK AND BLUE.\nEditor, The News:\nLIOR several years we have been\n1 fed on the theory that only poli\nticians are princes of purity and\nhence fit to govern American people.\nCertain local civic groups appar\nently have been affected by this\npropaganda and, as a result, are\nclamoring for the Government to\ntake over the street car systems.\nThose of us that have not forgot\nten the war, when our transporta\ntion systems not only were mis\nmanaged but were all but wrecked,\nare completely at the mercy of poli\nticians.\nJEFFERSONIAN DEMOCRAT.\ntrade quotas and special arrangements and the barriers which\nprotect them ano to throw all trade open to all on terms of\nequality.\nGermany proposed a compromise which would be in effect\nlittle more than a barter deal.\nHull could not accept any\ncompromise\u2014he turned his back finally on barter deals when\nhe won on a showdown with George Peek, who was Room\nvelt\u2019s foreign-trade adviser earlier in the New Deal\nAnother difficulty concerns our anti-dumping legislation,\nwhich has been the subject of long controversy with Germany.\nUnder her managed economy she has frequently been charged\nwith subsidizing exports in violation of the anti-dumping\nUnder her present methods of industrial manage\nclause.\nment and finance there would be great difficulty in enforcing\nour tariff provisions against dumping, enough at least to dis\ncourage our officials from wishing to have that problem in\ntheir hair.\nOur Government is more anxious to see the British Empire\nbrought within the network of the reciprocal program\nEf\nforts are being made to bring other democratic nations in.\nThen, with that vast amount of world trade established on a\nfree-moving basis, with most-favored-nation equality, it is felt\nthat proposals might be made to the German-Italian-Japanese\nbloc which would offer some hope of relieving their difficulties\nwith regard to raw materials, and thus open a path towaid\npeaceable adjustment of the tensions which are now so threat\nening\nPlain Economics\nby John T. Flynn\nNEW YORK\u2014The statement of Chairman William O.\nDouglas of the SEC on the commission\u2019s stock exchange poli\ncies is viewed in Wall-st as a threat on three of the Stock\nExchange's most cherished possessions.\nThey are the rule\nof the securities market by the traders, the right of special\nists to speculate on their own accounts, and the right of bro\nkers to engage in floor trading on a large scale.\nThe chairman of the commission\nmakes it plain that he prefers what\nhe calls 'self-government\" of the se\ncurity market to direct government\nby the commission.\nmates that self\ng o vernment\nought to be in\nthe hands of\nthose elements\nwhich represent\nmost\naccurately\nthe interests of\nthe investing\npublic.\nThis is a point\nof the greatest\nimportance. The\nmost conserva\ntive businessman\n1\nwill\ntake\nthe\nBut he inti\nA\nFlynn\nview that private business interests\nought to have the opportunity to\nmanage their own house. In this\ncase the house is the stock market.\nBut what are the private interests\nthat are to be found in the stock\nmarket? They are stock brokers,\nspecialists,\ninvestors,\ncorporation\nmanagement and moneylenders\u2014\nchiefly bankers and banks.\nIf this conservative view is sound,\nthen it is these private interests\nwhich ought to have the right to\ngovern the market.\nAs matters stand, however, they\ndo not. The government of the\nmarket is in the hands of just one\nof these groups. And it is the group\nwhich, of all those named, is the\nleast capable of\ngoverning\nthe\nmarket wisely. The market is now\ngoverned by a small number of stock\nA. F. of L Economists Hopeful\nof Early Business Revival\nA. F. of L. economists are far from\npessimistic over prospects of an\nearly resumption of recovery.\nIn its Monthly Survey of Business\ntoday the federation noted a num\nber of factors working for a revival\nof production \"in the near future.\u201d\nAmong these is listed large depres\nsion shortages in building, rail\nequipment, electrical and industrial\nmachinery and consumer goods.\nWage increases, it said. have lift\ned worker buying power to levels\njustifying expansion of consumers'\ngoods \u201cas soon as current inventories\nare consumed, and workers tempo\nrarily laid off return to work.\u201d Real\nwages in October were 7 per cent\nabove last year, and wage increases\nhave not prevented a steady rise in\ncorporation profits, it asserted.\nThe federation pointed\nto the\ngreat housing shortage, the utilities\u2019\nneed of replacements and expansion\ntotaling some $1,000,000,000 a year\nand other needs in the heavy goods\nIt blamed\nfields.\nthe industrial\nslowing down on a too-rapid rise in\nprices, and said the stock market\nslump was a \u201cwholesome adjustment\nof excessively high stock prices.\u201d\n\u201cThe present decline appears to\nbe a temporary check in our prog\nress toward higher production vol\numes and higher standards of liv\ning,\u201d the Survey stated, \u201cwhile busi\nbrokers who are members of the\nStock Exchange. But it is worse\nthan this. All brokers are not alike.\nSome are truly brokers, men who\nrepresent their customers in buy\ning and selling stocks. But others\n\u2014and these are the most numerous\n\u2014are speculators, gamblers in stocks.\nIt is a fact that for many years\nthe Stock Exchange has been truly\nbrokers, men who represent their\ncustomers in buying and selling\nstocks. But others\u2014and these are\nthe most numerous\u2014are speculators,\ngamblers in stocks.\nIt is a fact that for many years\nthe Stock Exchange has been domi\nnated by the speculation elements\nin it and not by those who are truly\nbrokers. And the result is that we\nhave not had self-government of\nthe market any more than we would\nhave self-government of a city if\nonly those in a single neighborhood\nwere allowed to vote.\nBecause the speculators control\nthe exchange, the rules of the ex\nchange inevitably favor their stake\nin the market. The speculators and,\nfor that matter, the brokers, are in\nterested in plenty of speculation.\nThey are not interested in the com\nmunity service or significance of\ntheir industry.\nis Commissioner Douglas suggest\ning that the stock markets ought to\nhave self-government in fact as\nwell as in name, instead of gov\nernment by only a single interest?\nThis hints at a very significant re\norganization of the markets and\none which is thoroly conservative.\nness waits for accumulated supplies\nto be bought off.\n\"Whether it will be of long dura\ntion depends to a very important\ndegree on our ability to maintain\nbuying power close to its present\nlevels, so that inventories of cloth\ning and household supplies may be\nquickly consumed and a strong mar\nket provided for durable consumer\ngoods, such as homes and automo\nbiles\"\nBAD HUMOR\nBy DAN KIDNEY\nMany steam-heated and\nover\nstuffed Americans sat around alter\na huge Thanksgiving dinner com\nplaining about how the Pilgrim\nFathers had it soft.\nSlogan for the House of Represent\n\"We also serve who only\natives:\nstand and talk.\"\nJudging from the crop quota for\nmula in the Senate farm bill, Ein\nstein is going to be Secretary of\nAgriculture.\nAnyway a slump at home taker,\nour minds off wars abroad.\nSafety First: Stay home and sur\nvive the holidays.","height":"21104","width":"14484"}}
